"```json\n{\n  \"Coding Problem\": \"Given is an integer N. Find the number of digits that N has in base K.\\n\\n-----Notes-----\\nFor information on base-K representation, see Positional notation - Wikipedia.\\n\\n-----Constraints-----\\n - All values in input are integers.\\n - 1 \\\\leq N \\\\leq 10^9\\n - 2 \\\\leq K \\\\leq 10\\n\\n-----Input-----\\nInput is given from Standard Input in the following format:\\nN K\\n\\n-----Output-----\\nPrint the number of digits that N has in base K.\\n\\n-----Sample Input-----\\n11 2\\n\\n-----Sample Output-----\\n4\\n\\nIn binary, 11 is represented as 1011.\",\n  \"Ground Truth Solution\": \"(N, K) = map(int, input().split())\\n(q, mod) = divmod(N, K)\\nmod_list = [mod]\\nwhile True:\\n\\t(q, mod) = divmod(q, K)\\n\\tmod_list.append(mod)\\n\\tif q <= 0:\\n\\t\\tbreak\\nif mod_list[-1] == 0:\\n\\tresult = len(mod_list) - 1\\nelse:\\n\\tresult = len(mod_list)\\nprint(result)\",\n  \"LLM CoT Steps Breakdown\": \"- Understand the problem: Given integers N and K, determine the number of digits required to represent N in base K.\\n- Devise a plan: Repeatedly divide N by K, counting the number of divisions until the quotient is zero. Each division represents one digit in base K.\\n- Implement the plan: Use a loop to perform the divisions and count the number of iterations. Handle the edge case when the last digit is zero by removing the digit from consideration.\\n- Consider Edge cases: N = 0, where the result is 1\",\n  \"LLM Questions\": [\n    \"What is base K representation and how does it relate to the number of digits?\",\n    \"How do you convert a number from base 10 to base K?\",\n    \"What are the edge cases to consider in this problem?\",\n    \"Could you explain the approach for finding the number of digits in base K?\",\n    \"How would you handle the special case where N is 0?\"\n  ],\n  \"Expected Answers to LLM Questions\": [\n    \"Base K representation is a way of representing numbers using K as the base. The number of digits required is directly related to the number of powers of K needed to represent the number.\",\n    \"To convert a number from base 10 to base K, you repeatedly divide the number by K and keep track of the remainders. These remainders, read in reverse order, form the base K representation.\",\n    \"Edge cases to consider include when N is 0 or when K is greater than N.\",\n    \"The approach involves repeatedly dividing N by K and counting the number of divisions (or remainders).  The loop continues until the quotient becomes 0. The count of divisions is the number of digits.\",\n    \"When N is 0, regardless of the base K, the number of digits required to represent it is 1 (just the digit 0).\"\n  ]\n}\n```"